name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: This is very broad strokes and doesn‚Äôt touch every element or trade off but the point is FB is and always will be a bad actor. It‚Äôs time to have a new 21st century vision of a digital public sphere that is driven by people + communities not profits + corporations. 14/14

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: We can regulate bad economic incentives wo regulating free speech.  Create a digitial bill of rights. Update anti-trust laws for digital platforms. Reform IP + labor laws. That‚Äôs the roadmap to fixing deeper problems of social media platforms that speech issues represent (13/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: And Big Tech like FB profits from this dynamic. Their profits come from devouring revenues of local press, small firms, and alt centers of power in our democracy which further erodes civic life (12/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: FB regulates free speech already. (And it privileges white supremacy). Their algorithms (and twitter YouTube etc) already filter us we just rarely see it that way. This means less powerful or popular voices get erased without most ppl noticing  (11/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: 3rd, it curbs corporate power in our political + economic life. 5 companies should not control the internet. Zuckerberg should not regulate speech. No one elected them. And consumers didn‚Äôt explicitly ‚Äúvote‚Äù for monopolies. They exploited loopholes and laziness in gov (10/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: Private networks can still exist. If you want to be a racist asshole, do it on the racist asshole platform. If you want to organize tenants wo your landlord knowing, do it. Private firms/orgs can offer those services + already do but won‚Äôt have quasi public responsibilities 9/14

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: 2nd, it would protect privacy. A digital public ID would make bots impossible and trolling socially costly but would also protect minors, prevent personal data from 3rd party exploitation and block fraud/cloaked influence (8/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: Public platforms would have inclusive incentives rather than exploitive incentives. It would help more ppl (disabled/elderly/parents) engage in civic life and encourage different behaviors in general online 7/14

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: 1st, we must create universal digital rights. Our world is online; every person must have equal access to a digital public sphere just like anyone can enter a library/town hall. Public platforms would be free, transparent about algorithms + could ban private data mining (6/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: So nationalizing @Facebook @Twitter (and @amazon and @Google) won‚Äôt stop hate speech per se, then why do it? I see 3 main reasons (5/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: Quick sidetrack - the irony of the @Harpers letter of course is it highlights in/out crowd regulation of free speech wo 1A. Our society oppresses plenty of speech ‚Äúlegally‚Äù through social norms + financial power. The letter is in-crowders not happy being challenged for it (4/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: We can attempt to legislate hate speech + harassment but it‚Äôs unlikely to win in courts which have a long history of protecting free speech + broadly defining it. Undoubtedly that‚Äôs privileged white supremacy in US but we can fight that wo ‚Äòregulating‚Äô free speech (3/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: Most obviously nationalizing social media platforms would not likely stop hate speech or harassment. It would actually protect them under 1A if it‚Äôs publicly owned - more than on a private platform at least. So that‚Äôs not by itself the reason to nationalize (2/14)

name: Pete üî•#CancelRentüî• Harrison
tweet: During the @NY1 debate @errollouis asked a rapid fire question about social media companies regulating free speech and I said it‚Äôs time we talk about nationalizing these platforms. After the FB audit, I wanted to eleborate on what I mean (but it‚Äôs way complicated) (1/14)
